english:
  title: Blue Words for the Lower Origin Ceremony
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    First Offering

    As the full moon of the ninth month gives way to the Lower Origin's autumn day, we pour the wine of reverence to offer sincerity, humbly beseeching the descent of blessing. May your precious gaze fall upon us, and bestow abundantly the grace of pure fortune.

    Second Offering

    Vast and boundless heaven stretches infinite, yet the Way preceded even chaos itself. Life stirs within creation's measure, yet destiny never escapes the Potter's hand. With utmost faith drawn from within, we dedicate ourselves to serve the subtle grace that flows downward to all below.

    Third Offering

    Embodying breath and holding fast to the origin, we borrow from all the mechanisms of creation and transformation. You survey merit and mark transgression, secretly wielding the powers of fortune and misfortune. How could we not pour forth our humble hearts in hope that you might hear?

    Yet I tremble—my virtue falls short, and my governance weighs heavy. Though I inherit the accumulated merit of generations past and shepherd the people as their guide, I have not yet glimpsed the efficacy worthy of Heaven's favor. In this season of accounting and record, my fearful devotion runs deep. Reverently I summon the companions of the immortals and humbly present the Royal Mandate. Grant that my faults be dissolved, that I might find ground for renewal. Let my years be inscribed in abundance, and let me receive the rare fortune of imperishable age.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Lower Origin (下元) refers to the fifteenth day of the tenth lunar month, an important Daoist ceremonial date associated with the earthly realm and water.
  - key: ''
    value: This is a ritual liturgy (靑詞) with three formal offerings, each introducing deepening layers of cosmological and political reflection—a common structure in Korean court Daoist ceremonies.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'companions of the immortals' (鶴侶) and 'Royal Mandate' (龍章) are poetic references to celestial sanction and heavenly endorsement of earthly rule.
